INSERT INTO modules (client_id, title, description, category, video_url, chapters, order_index)
SELECT
  NULL,
  'Using Claude to Compound Your Operations',
  'Turn Claude into real operating leverage — what it can do, the two surfaces, skills, connectors, and the operator hygiene to use it without becoming dependent.',
  'Backend Optimisation',
  NULL,
  '[{"title":"Chapter 1 — What Claude is and what it can do","lessons":[{"title":"What Claude is and what it can do","body":"Most operators who hear \"AI tool\" think of one of two things: a chatbot like ChatGPT, or some kind of \"automation\" that requires technical setup. Claude is neither, and understanding what it actually is will determine whether you use it as a toy or as leverage.\n\nClaude is an AI model built by Anthropic — a company whose entire research focus is making AI systems that are useful, honest, and safe. The model itself is what does the work: reading what you write, understanding the context, and producing a response. You access this model through two surfaces.\n\nThe first is **Claude.ai** — a chat interface you open in your browser or on your phone. You type, Claude responds. This is what most people picture when they think of AI. Free to start, paid tiers for heavier use.\n\nThe second is **Claude Code** — a tool that runs in your computer''s terminal (the text-based command interface developers use). Unlike Claude.ai, Claude Code can actually do things on your computer: read your files, write new ones, run commands, modify entire projects. If you don''t write code, you might think this is irrelevant. It isn''t — but we''ll get there in Chapter 2.\n\nFor now, what matters is this: the same Claude model powers both surfaces. The difference is what each surface can touch. Claude.ai talks. Claude Code talks AND acts.\n\n## The mental model worth carrying\n\nClaude is a fast, tireless analyst-writer-coder that needs a competent operator pointing it at the right work. It is not an oracle. It is not a magic answer machine. It is leverage on what you already know.\n\nThink of Claude the way you''d think of hiring a junior analyst who never sleeps, has read most of the internet up to a certain date, can write in nearly any style if you show them examples, but has no taste, no judgment about what matters in your business, and will confidently make things up if you don''t catch it.\n\nThat last part is critical: Claude can hallucinate. It can produce a confident, well-structured answer that''s factually wrong. Always verify claims before you use Claude''s output in anything that matters.\n\n## What Claude is genuinely good at\n\n**Drafting at scale.** Hooks, scripts, DMs, emails, SOPs, sales copy — anything text-based. Output quality scales directly with the context you give it. A vague prompt like \"write me an Instagram caption\" produces generic output. A prompt with your past three captions, your target audience, the goal of the post, and the tone you want produces something usable. The pattern is consistent across every drafting task: more context in, better output out.\n\n**Analysis.** Read a transcript, a CSV, a long document, and pull out patterns, themes, or summaries. If you record sales calls or coaching calls, you can paste the transcript and get a structured breakdown in seconds — what landed, what didn''t, what the client''s actual blocker is, what to follow up on. The same pattern works for content audits, competitor research, performance reviews.\n\n**Structured outputs.** Take messy inputs and turn them into clean tables, lists, JSON, or formatted documents. Useful any time you''d otherwise be reformatting manually. Example: paste 20 testimonials, ask Claude to extract the recurring themes and rank them by frequency. What would take an hour manually takes 30 seconds with Claude.\n\n**Code.** Even if you don''t write code yourself, Claude can. You can describe what you want in plain English — \"build me a simple form that takes a name and email and saves it to a Google Sheet\" — and Claude will produce working code. With Claude Code, it will actually create the files and walk you through deploying them. This is where one-person coaching businesses unlock automations they couldn''t build before.\n\n**Working across files.** When using Claude Code, it can read, write, and modify entire codebases. Multi-file tasks that would take hours manually finish in minutes. If you have client SOPs, transcripts, or content drafts scattered across folders, Claude Code can read all of them, identify patterns, and produce a unified output.\n\n## Where Claude falls short\n\n**Real-time facts.** Claude''s knowledge has a cutoff date — typically a few months before you''re talking to it. Ask it for today''s stock price, last week''s news, or what''s currently trending on Instagram and it will tell you it doesn''t know, or worse, make something up. For current data, it can search the web — but that''s slower, and you should always verify before relying on the result.\n\n**Original creative work.** This is the most misunderstood limit. Claude can imitate styles and frameworks brilliantly. Show it five of your hooks, and it''ll generate fifty more in the same style. But it cannot invent a worldview, a brand voice, or a strategic angle that doesn''t already exist in the inputs you give it. The taste — knowing which of those fifty hooks is actually any good — is the irreplaceable layer you bring. AI doesn''t replace operator taste. It demands more of it.\n\n**Anything with no verifiable answer.** If a decision is genuinely 50/50 — \"should I price my offer at $4k or $5k?\" — Claude will produce a confident answer anyway. It will reason through it, give you considerations, and arrive at a recommendation. But the recommendation isn''t based on knowing your business better than you do. It''s based on patterns in its training data, applied to the inputs you gave. Use Claude to surface considerations. Don''t outsource the decision itself.\n\n## One last frame before we move on\n\nThe operators who get the most out of Claude treat it like a senior collaborator they''re directing, not a junior assistant they''re delegating to. They give detailed context. They challenge the output. They verify claims. They iterate. They use Claude to compress work that used to take hours into work that takes minutes — but they remain the operator. The decisions, the taste, the judgment, the strategic direction — those still come from them.\n\nIf you take one thing from this chapter: Claude is not a replacement for you. It''s a multiplier for what you can already do. If you can''t draft a decent DM, Claude won''t make your DMs decent — it will just generate mediocre DMs faster. The work you do to develop your own judgment and skill never stops mattering.\n\n> **Do this now:** Open Claude.ai. If you don''t have an account, sign up — the free tier is enough for this exercise. Paste in one piece of your own content from the last week: a DM you sent a prospect, an email you wrote to a client, a script you posted. Then write this prompt: \"Identify what''s working and what''s weak about this. Be specific. Don''t hedge.\" Read the output critically. What does Claude catch that you missed? What does it miss that you caught? That gap — what Claude misses — is your taste. Pay attention to it. It''s the layer that makes you irreplaceable.","links":[]}]},{"title":"Chapter 2 — Claude.ai vs Claude Code — which to use when","lessons":[{"title":"Claude.ai vs Claude Code — which to use when","body":"Both surfaces use the same Claude model underneath. The difference is what they can touch, and understanding that difference saves you from using the wrong tool for the wrong job.\n\nHere''s the simplest way to remember it:\n\n- **Claude.ai talks.** It responds to messages, generates text, analyzes things you paste in. It cannot do anything to your computer.\n- **Claude Code acts.** It runs on your machine, reads your files, writes new ones, executes commands. It can build things, modify things, deploy things.\n\nThat distinction is the whole chapter. Everything else is just consequences of it.\n\n## Claude.ai in detail\n\nClaude.ai is the chat interface. You go to claude.ai in your browser, or download the mobile app, and you have a conversation with Claude. Same shape as ChatGPT, Gemini, or any other AI chat product.\n\nInside the chat, you can:\n\n- Type messages and get responses\n- Upload files (PDFs, images, documents) for Claude to read\n- Have Claude search the web for current information\n- Use a code sandbox where Claude can run code in a limited, contained environment\n- Generate images and visualizations\n- Save and reuse skills (which you''ll learn about in Chapter 3)\n- Connect to external services like Gmail, Notion, and Google Drive (Chapter 5)\n\nWhat Claude.ai cannot do:\n\n- Modify files on your computer\n- Run terminal commands\n- Persist data between sessions unless you save it yourself\n- Execute multi-step tasks autonomously across your file system\n- Deploy code or push changes to live systems\n\nClaude.ai is designed for thinking, drafting, analyzing, and conversation. It''s accessible from any device with a browser. You can use it on your phone in line at a coffee shop. You can switch laptops and your Claude.ai history is still there because it''s stored in your account.\n\n## Claude Code in detail\n\nClaude Code is a command-line tool. To use it, you open your computer''s terminal — on Mac, that''s the Terminal app; on Windows, it''s PowerShell or Command Prompt; on Linux, it''s whatever shell you''re running. Then you type `claude` and hit Enter. A Claude conversation starts right there in the terminal.\n\nThe difference from Claude.ai is that this Claude is inside your computer. It can:\n\n- Read any file on your machine you point it at\n- Write new files anywhere you let it\n- Run terminal commands (install software, run scripts, push to GitHub, deploy to a server)\n- Work across an entire project — for example, you can say \"go through every file in this folder and fix the typos,\" and it will\n- Maintain state across a single working session as it edits and tests its own work\n\nYou install Claude Code once (Anthropic''s documentation walks you through it — it''s a 5-minute setup if you''re comfortable in the terminal, 30 minutes if you''ve never opened one before). After that, every time you want to use it, you open the terminal, navigate to whatever project folder you want it to work in, and run `claude`.\n\nFor non-developers, Claude Code sounds intimidating. Here''s the honest read: you do not need Claude Code to get the bulk of the value from Claude. Most coaches will live in Claude.ai 95% of the time. But there''s one thing Claude Code does better than Claude.ai, and it matters even for non-developers: managing your skill files. We''ll cover that in Chapter 3.\n\n## Decision rules — when to use which\n\n| Use Claude.ai when | Use Claude Code when |\n| --- | --- |\n| Drafting content, scripts, emails, DMs | Modifying files in a real project on your computer |\n| Brainstorming, analyzing a transcript | Writing or debugging code |\n| One-off questions, quick analysis | Multi-step tasks that touch many files |\n| Working from your phone or any browser | Anything where Claude needs to run commands |\n| Sharing context with someone else | Operations on your local codebase |\n| Using your skills from any device | Building or editing skill files on disk |\n\n## The 80/20 of what most operators actually need\n\nIf you run a coaching, consulting, or content-based business and you''re not a developer:\n\n- **Day-to-day ops live in Claude.ai.** Drafting content, analyzing calls, writing DMs, summarizing transcripts, briefing setters, planning content batches. All of it works in the chat interface.\n- **Anything technical lives in Claude Code.** Building a custom portal, automating a workflow, integrating two pieces of software, deploying a landing page. If you''re not building these things, you don''t need Claude Code for this purpose.\n\nBut — and this is where most operators get stuck — there''s a third use case that sits between the two: managing your skill files.\n\nSkills (Chapter 3) are small markdown files that tell Claude how to act in a specific context. You can upload them to Claude.ai and they''ll work on any device. You can also save them on your computer, where Claude Code can read and edit them directly.\n\nIf you only use Claude.ai, your skills live in your Claude.ai account and sync across devices. That works fine. If you want to back them up, share them, or edit them faster, Claude Code is the cleaner tool. We''ll cover both paths in the next chapter — no preference yet.\n\n## Common mistakes the first time\n\nThree things tend to confuse first-time users:\n\n**Mistake 1: Trying to make Claude.ai modify files on your computer.** It can''t. You can upload a file for Claude to read, but you can''t ask it to \"save changes back to the file\" — Claude.ai doesn''t have write access to your machine. If you need that, use Claude Code.\n\n**Mistake 2: Using Claude Code for tasks that don''t need it.** Drafting a DM in Claude Code is overkill. Open Claude.ai for that. Claude Code is for when you actually need the terminal access — multi-file edits, running commands, building things.\n\n**Mistake 3: Not realizing they''re the same model.** People sometimes think Claude.ai is \"the simple version\" and Claude Code is \"the advanced version.\" It isn''t. Same model, same capability ceiling, different surfaces. Whatever Claude can think, both versions can think. The only difference is what they can do with that thinking.\n\n> **Do this now:** Open Claude.ai and ask it: \"Walk me through how to install Claude Code on my computer. Assume I''ve never used a terminal before. Give me numbered steps.\" Don''t necessarily install it yet — just read what it tells you and assess whether the install feels accessible to you. If it does, install it and run `claude` once just to see the prompt come up. If it doesn''t, stay in Claude.ai for now — you can revisit Claude Code in three months when you have a specific reason to use it. The point of this exercise isn''t to install Claude Code. It''s to know what''s available so you can reach for it when the time comes.","links":[]}]},{"title":"Chapter 3 — Setting up your first skill","lessons":[{"title":"Setting up your first skill","body":"This is the chapter that, if you actually do the exercise at the end, changes how you operate forever. Not exaggeration — measured fact. The operators who use AI as a real leverage tool versus those who use it as a fancy chatbot is almost entirely determined by whether they build skills.\n\n## What a skill actually is\n\nA skill is a small text file written in markdown (a simple formatting language — don''t worry, you don''t need to learn it deeply) that tells Claude how to act in a specific context.\n\nImagine you debrief every coaching call the same way: you want to know what landed, what didn''t, what the client''s real blocker is, and what the next action should be. Without a skill, every time you debrief a call, you have to either type out those instructions to Claude or load the context manually. After 50 calls, you''ve typed the same instructions 50 times.\n\nWith a skill, you write those instructions once. Save them as a file. Upload to Claude.ai (or save to your computer if you''re using Claude Code). Then every time you have a call to debrief, you just say \"debrief this call\" and paste the transcript. Claude loads the skill, follows the instructions, and produces the debrief in your exact format. Every. Single. Time.\n\nThat''s the entire point of skills: write the context once, reuse it forever.\n\n## Anatomy of a skill — two parts only\n\nEvery skill is made of exactly two things:\n\n**1. YAML frontmatter** — the metadata at the top of the file. It tells Claude what the skill is called and when to use it. It looks like this:\n\n```yaml\n---\nname: client-debrief\ndescription: Use this skill when I share a call transcript. Trigger phrases — \"debrief this call\", \"review this transcript\".\n---\n```\n\nThree things to notice:\n\n- The triple dashes (`---`) above and below — those mark the start and end of the metadata block\n- `name` — what the skill is called. Use lowercase, hyphens between words, no spaces\n- `description` — when Claude should use this skill. Include trigger phrases here. This is what Claude looks at to decide \"should I activate this skill right now?\"\n\nThe description matters more than people realize. If it''s vague (\"for call stuff\"), Claude won''t know when to fire it. If it''s specific (\"Use this skill when I share a call transcript\"), Claude knows exactly when to activate.\n\n**2. Body content** — the actual instructions. Plain text in markdown format. Tell Claude what to do, what voice to use, what NOT to do, and what to output. It goes below the closing `---` and runs to the bottom of the file.\n\nThat''s it. Two parts. A skill is just a markdown file with metadata at the top and instructions below.\n\n## A complete working example — copy this\n\nHere''s a real, working skill for debriefing coaching calls. Save it as a file called `client-debrief.md` on your computer (any text editor works — Notes, TextEdit, VSCode, Sublime, whatever):\n\n```markdown\n---\nname: client-debrief\ndescription: Use this skill whenever I share a call transcript with a coaching client. Pulls out what landed, what didn''t, the client''s actual blocker, and the next action. Trigger phrases — \"debrief this call\", \"review this transcript\", \"what happened on this call\".\n---\n\n# Client Call Debrief\n\nWhen I share a transcript, produce a debrief with these sections:\n\n## What landed\nThe 2-3 strongest moments. Where the client got real or made a commitment.\n\n## What didn''t land\nWhere coaching missed. Where I over-talked, gave a framework instead of a question, or accepted a soft commitment.\n\n## Client''s actual blocker\nStrip away what the client said the problem was. What''s the real pattern? (Avoidance? Execution gap? Identity issue? Outsourcing decision-making?)\n\n## Next 7 days\nThe ONE thing the client needs to do or face by next call. Be specific.\n\n## My WhatsApp follow-up\nA short message I''d send. My voice — direct, no preamble, no emojis. Reference only what came up in this call.\n```\n\nThat''s a real skill. Working operators use versions of this every day. Notice what the skill does and does not do:\n\n- It tells Claude the structure of the output (five sections)\n- It tells Claude the tone of each section (specific, not vague)\n- It tells Claude the voice to use in the follow-up message (direct, no preamble, no emojis)\n- It does NOT include the call transcript itself — that gets pasted into the chat when you use the skill\n\nThat last part is critical: the skill is the instructions. The data (the transcript) is what you give Claude in the actual conversation. Don''t try to bake the data into the skill file.\n\n## How to upload to Claude.ai (the easier path for most operators)\n\n1. Open Claude.ai in your browser\n2. Click your profile icon (top right or bottom left depending on the layout)\n3. Go to Settings → Capabilities → Skills (the exact menu name might vary; look for \"Skills\")\n4. Click \"Add skill\" or \"Upload skill\"\n5. Select your `client-debrief.md` file from your computer\n6. Save\n\nThat''s it. The skill is now active in your Claude.ai account. To use it, open any conversation, paste a call transcript, and write \"debrief this call.\" Claude loads the skill and follows the instructions.\n\nThe Claude.ai approach has one big advantage: skills uploaded here sync across all your devices. Mac, phone, second laptop — same skill, available everywhere.\n\n## How to set it up via Claude Code (the path for operators who want more control)\n\n1. Open your terminal\n2. Make a folder for the skill: `mkdir -p ~/.claude/skills/client-debrief`\n3. Save the file inside as `SKILL.md` (not `client-debrief.md` — the convention for Claude Code is to use `SKILL.md` as the filename, and the folder name becomes the skill''s identifier)\n4. Done. Next time you run Claude Code from any folder on your computer, the skill is available\n\nThe advantage of the Claude Code path: skills are real files on your machine, so you can version-control them with git, back them up, edit them in your favorite text editor, share them with other operators, sync them across machines via Dropbox or iCloud. The disadvantage: only works on the machine where the file exists.\n\nMost operators end up using both: Claude.ai for skills they want available everywhere, Claude Code for skills they''re actively developing or that contain sensitive information they don''t want stored in Claude.ai''s cloud.\n\n## Common mistakes when writing your first skill\n\n**Mistake 1: Making the skill too generic.** \"Help me with my content\" isn''t a skill. It''s a wish. A skill needs to specify exactly what context, what format, what voice, what NOT to do. The more specific, the better the output.\n\n**Mistake 2: Writing the description without trigger phrases.** If your description is just \"for client work,\" Claude won''t know when to activate it. Include the actual phrases you''ll use: \"debrief this call,\" \"draft a follow-up DM,\" \"review this email.\" Make it easy for Claude to recognize when the skill applies.\n\n**Mistake 3: Trying to make one skill do everything.** Don''t write a \"ClientStuff\" skill that handles onboarding, debriefs, and DM drafts all at once. Make three small skills. Each one focused. Skills are cheap to create and easy to combine.\n\n**Mistake 4: Not iterating.** Your first skill will not be your best skill. Use it for a week. Notice where the output disappoints you. Edit the skill to address that gap. Run it again. Iterate. After three rounds of iteration, the skill produces output you''d struggle to differentiate from your own work.\n\n**Mistake 5: Including credentials or secrets in the skill body.** API keys, passwords, tokens — don''t paste these into a skill file you upload to Claude.ai (they get stored in your account). If a skill needs credentials, use environment variables or keep that skill local in Claude Code, never on Claude.ai''s cloud.\n\n## Why this changes everything\n\nAfter your third skill, something shifts. You stop typing the same context over and over. You stop explaining your voice every time. You stop reformatting outputs. The work that used to take 30 minutes per instance — debriefing a call, drafting a follow-up, summarizing a transcript — now takes 30 seconds. And the output quality is better, because the skill captures patterns and constraints you wouldn''t have remembered to include if you were typing it out from scratch each time.\n\nFive well-built skills replace roughly 8-10 hours of repetitive work per week for a one-person coaching business. That''s not a theoretical claim. That''s measurement.\n\n> **Do this now:** Write your first skill. Don''t aim for perfect — aim for shipped. Pick the most-repeated context-loading task in your business — call debriefs, content drafts, DM templates, weekly review. Open a text editor. Write the YAML frontmatter (name + description with trigger phrases). Write the body — what should Claude do, what format, what voice, what to avoid. Save the file as a `.md`. Upload to Claude.ai. Use it on a real task today. Don''t move on to Chapter 4 until you''ve used your first skill at least once on actual work. The chapter only matters if you''ve done this.","links":[]}]},{"title":"Chapter 4 — The five skill patterns every coach needs","lessons":[{"title":"The five skill patterns every coach needs","body":"Five patterns cover 80% of what a one-person coaching business does repeatedly. Build these in order — voice first, because every other skill stacks on top of it.\n\n## 1. Voice skill\n\nA file describing how you actually talk, write, and think on camera. What words you use, what you never use, the rhythm of your sentences, the lens you bring to topics. Without this, every Claude-drafted piece of content sounds like a generic AI coach.\n\nWhat goes in it: your most common phrases, banned vocabulary, sentence-length preferences, examples of your best content (paste actual posts/scripts), the topics you do and don''t talk about, your filming aesthetic.\n\n## 2. Content skill\n\nThe frameworks you use repeatedly to make content. Your hook formulas. Your reel structure. Your carousel beats. Your VSL flow. Each piece of content has a structure — the content skill encodes that so you don''t rebuild it every time.\n\nWhat goes in it: hook patterns that worked, content lanes you stay inside, framework templates (e.g., \"BAB structure: before → after → bridge\"), what topics map to what formats.\n\n## 3. Call debrief skill\n\nTurn raw Fathom/Loom/Zoom transcripts into structured post-call breakdowns. What landed, what didn''t, root-cause patterns, next actions, follow-up message.\n\nThis is the skill that compounds your coaching most. By call 20 with a client, you can identify patterns across 20 debriefs in seconds — something that''s impossible from memory alone.\n\n## 4. Client onboarding skill\n\nTurn a new client''s intake form, sales call transcript, and initial questionnaire into a structured profile: their ICP, their unique mechanism, their proof library, their blockers, their tonality issues. Saves 2-3 hours per new client and gives you a single source of truth to reference.\n\n## 5. SOP skill\n\nAny repeated workflow that has more than 3 steps deserves a skill. Examples: scheduling content, briefing a setter, weekly KPI review, monthly retro. Write the workflow once. Trigger it whenever you do it. Iterate on the file as the SOP evolves.\n\n## Sequence matters\n\nBuild voice first. Without it, content skills produce AI-sounding output. Build content second. Build debrief third (it''s the highest-frequency reuse). Onboarding and SOP follow once the first three are stable.\n\n> **Do this now:** Write your voice skill. Open Claude.ai. Spend 30 minutes pasting 5-10 of your strongest pieces of content into a doc. Ask Claude to extract patterns: rhythm, vocabulary, lens. Use that as the body of your `voice` skill. Test it by asking Claude (with the skill loaded) to draft a piece of content in your voice. Compare to your real voice. Iterate.","links":[]}]},{"title":"Chapter 5 — Connecting Claude to your stack","lessons":[{"title":"Connecting Claude to your stack","body":"Skills give Claude context. Connectors give Claude access. Claude can connect to external tools through a system called MCP (Model Context Protocol). When connected, Claude can read your Gmail, query your Notion, search your Drive, check your Calendar — all without you having to copy-paste data into the chat.\n\n## The four connectors worth setting up first\n\n**1. Gmail**\n\nRead inbox, search messages, draft replies. Useful for: triaging client emails, finding past conversations, drafting follow-ups using your real reply patterns.\n\nRisk: Gmail access is broad. Claude can read everything by default. Use carefully on sensitive accounts.\n\n**2. Notion**\n\nRead pages, query databases, create new entries. Useful for: pulling client data from your dashboard, logging new clients to a queue, querying past project notes.\n\nLower risk than Gmail because Notion content is usually less sensitive than email.\n\n**3. Google Drive**\n\nSearch files, read documents, read spreadsheets. Useful for: referencing past sales decks, pulling transcript files, finding old SOPs.\n\nTip: organize your Drive before connecting. A messy Drive returns messy results.\n\n**4. Google Calendar**\n\nRead events, check availability, create new entries. Useful for: scheduling client calls without leaving chat, finding gaps for content batches, retrieving past meeting details.\n\n## How to connect\n\nIn Claude.ai → Settings → Connectors → Add. Each connector goes through OAuth (you authorize Claude to access your account). You can revoke access any time.\n\n## The safety rule\n\nTreat connectors like access to your assistant. You wouldn''t give an assistant your bank login. Same logic. Connect tools that hold business-critical context. Don''t connect tools that hold private personal data unless you have a specific reason.\n\n> **Do this now:** Connect ONE tool. Recommendation: Notion if you keep client data there, or Gmail if your inbox is your operating layer. After connecting, test it with a simple query: \"Find my last 3 emails from [client name]\" or \"What''s in the [database] in Notion?\". Don''t connect everything at once — adopt one, use it for a week, then add the next.","links":[]}]},{"title":"Chapter 6 — Operator hygiene","lessons":[{"title":"Operator hygiene","body":"Claude is a force multiplier. Without operator hygiene, it multiplies bad inputs into bad outputs at scale. Six rules that separate operators who use AI well from operators who become dependent on it.\n\n## 1. When NOT to use Claude\n\n- **High-stakes decisions where being wrong matters.** Pricing your offer, firing a team member, choosing between two strategic forks. Use Claude to surface considerations. Don''t use it to make the call.\n- **Original creative work.** Your worldview, brand voice, strategic angle, big creative bets — these have to come from you. Claude can refine them. It cannot invent them.\n- **Anything where you need to prove you know something.** Sales calls, coaching sessions, content where authority matters. If you can''t do it without Claude, you can''t sell it.\n\n## 2. Always verify outputs before using\n\nClaude makes mistakes. It hallucinates facts, invents statistics, attributes things to the wrong people. Before you use any Claude output in client-facing or revenue-bearing work, verify the claims. Treat every output as a draft, never a final.\n\n## 3. Credentials are dangerous\n\nSkills can hold API keys, passwords, tokens. If you build skills with sensitive credentials, remember:\n\n- Never paste real credentials into a Claude.ai chat (they get logged)\n- For Claude Code skills with credentials: store the file outside any git repo\n- Rotate any credential that has appeared in a chat transcript\n\n## 4. The input-stacking trap\n\nThe most insidious failure mode. Claude makes it easy to keep gathering inputs — frameworks, perspectives, drafts, council outputs, analyses. None of which ship.\n\nSign you''re in the trap: you''ve used Claude for 2+ hours today and produced zero outputs that left your laptop. The fix: cap the number of Claude sessions per day on any single decision. If you''ve used Claude three times on the same question, you don''t need a fourth output. You need to decide.\n\n## 5. The taste-and-judgment rule\n\nClaude can produce 100 hooks in five minutes. Of those, maybe 3-5 will be good enough to use. Your job is to identify which 3-5. If you can''t tell the difference between a good hook and a mediocre one, more hooks doesn''t help — it just produces more mediocre output faster. Develop taste before scaling output.\n\n## 6. Sync across machines if you work across machines\n\nLocal Claude Code skills live on the machine you wrote them on. If you switch laptops, the skill doesn''t follow. Either:\n\n- Use Claude.ai user skills (sync automatically)\n- Sync your `~/.claude/skills/` directory via Dropbox, iCloud, or git\n- Keep a single master device where Claude Code lives\n\n> **Do this now:** Audit your last week. Count how many Claude sessions you ran. Count how many of them produced output that shipped (an email sent, content posted, a client deliverable). If the ratio is below 50%, you''re in the input-stacking trap. Cut your sessions in half this week and force yourself to ship from each one.","links":[]}]}]'::jsonb,
  8
WHERE NOT EXISTS (
  SELECT 1 FROM modules WHERE title = 'Using Claude to Compound Your Operations'
);
